\begin_layout Standard
Since there is board to board communication on top of interacting with the OLED screen in this checkoff,
 there needs to be set pins required for transmitting and receiving the data,
 which we decided in implement pin 1 and 2 for,
 since they were no longer needed for I2C.
 We had a pretty good OLED display working using SPI,
 so we also used the setup from that lab as well.
 Using the previous part,
 we also can press buttons onto the MCU,
 and then we can decode what it says now.
 We just had to implement out how they would communicate to each other through UART,
 and what specific graphics we wanted to show on the display.
 Based on those 2 things,
 along with switching the output pin of the IR receiver to 6,
 we then created the pinmux config.
\end_layout

